title: Liverpool, Liverpool University Library Special Collections & Archives, MS.Ed.7-10
summary: Fragments from a late 15th century Italian antiphoner.
description:
Four parchment leaves from an antiphoner, measuring c.530-580 x 390-400 mm. Square notation on red four-line staff. Chants for Palm Sunday, Ascension, Corpus Christi, and Common of Apostles.

Decoration: Each leaf has a large historiated initial: I: Christ standing (foliated in red ccxi); P: Christ showing his wounds (lxxxv); I: the Holy Sacrament (cxxxix);  I: putto head and scroll, In natale apostolorum. The first two initials attributable to the illuminator Antonio Maria Sforza, according to MERT, citing Canova (plates 145-149).

Provenance 1450-1500. 

Acquired by Sir C. Sydney Jones ca. 1919 from Young's for the School of Education Library, University of Liverpool. Later transferred to the University Library.

The above is based on the description from the library (https://libguides.liverpool.ac.uk/library/sca/LULMSED7-10_fragment).
However, the attribution that it is "likely to be from the Benedictine monastery of Santa Giustina at Padua (MMM1993, 24)" is based entirely on the style of the miniatures, and not the chant contents.

Fragmentarium entry: https://fragmentarium.ms/overview/F-lmov
selected_bibliography:
G. Mariani Canova, La miniatura Veneta del Rinascimento (Venice, 1969)

Medieval Manuscripts on Merseyside,1993. University Art Gallery, Liverpool and Courtauld Institute Galleries, London. (Item 34.)

Medieval and Early Renaissance Treasures in the North West, 1976. Whitworth Art Gallery, Manchester. Item 76.

title: Budapest, Magyar Tudományos Akadémia Könyvtár és Információs Központ, T 174
description:
Single page of an unnoted breviary, unknown and somewhat atypical usage. Two column layout. Northern textualis script with Praegothica features, 13th century. 

Used as a binding in the mid-fifteenth (?) century. The subsequent volume was at one time in the collection of the Ochsenhausen monastery in Baden-Württemberg, which may point to a German origin. 

Fragment is in several horizontal strips, which together give a folio of 263×210 mm with a written height of 230 mm (32 lines). 
Chants and readings for Mark (April 25) and Philip and James (May 1), with apparently a single antiphon for Walpurgis (also May 1). 
Mark readings taken from Passio Sancti Marci, BHL 5276; a significant portion is missing at the bottom of the page.

title: Dublin, Royal Society of Antiquaries of Ireland, Box 41 #38
summary: 14th century missal from Devon, England. Four line red staff, square notation; both C and F clefs used.  Approximately 300x200mm (exact measurements of original impossible to determine due to damage.) Written space 190x125 mm in two columns, separated by 15 mm. 12 staves per page (36 written lines on text pages).
description:
[Most of this description is summarized from O'Neill, "A manuscript missal," 2018]

Damaged fourteenth-century missal recovered in the nineteenth century from a house in Ashprington, near Totnes, Devon; likely the missal belonged to the medieval parish church of St David's. 

Only two chants are given with notation. Many of the quires are lost, as is the binding, and what remains is charred and highly fragile.

Originally the missal probably comprised some 175 folios, of which 63 survive. 

The script suggests a mid-to-late fourteenth century date, and the surviving initials are similar to those of English manuscripts of the mid-fourteenth century. The inclusion of Relic Sunday on the Sunday after the feast of Thomas Becket points to a Sarum use after the year 1319. 
In the calendar, a later hand has added St David and St Chad, which may have occurred after the upgrading of these saints in England in 1415; it is also possible that the missal was acquired by St David's parish during its fifteenth-century refurbishment, and these saints added at that time. References to the pope have been removed throughout, meaning the missal was still in public use at the time of Henry VIII's edict of 1539.

Parts of ten quires survive, most of which were originally eight folios. It is possible to estimate that  some seven or eight quires are missing from the Temporale, and a similar number from the Sanctorale; thus what survives is approximately one-third of the original missal. 

Most of the missal is not notated. However, there are two columns of chant for the liturgical reading of the genealogy at Epiphany, in a mode 3 formula; why this is written out, and few other chants, is not obvious. Similarly, St Anne is given a sequence written out in full; possibly this reflects the relative novelty of the feast of St Anne, which was given official status in a papal bull transmitted by the Archbishop of Canterbury in 1383.

[Most of this description is summarized from O'Neill, "A manuscript missal," 2018]

Damaged fourteenth-century missal recovered in the nineteenth century from a house in Ashprington, near Totnes, Devon; likely the missal belonged to the medieval parish church of St David's.

Only two chants are given with notation. Many of the quires are lost, as is the binding, and what remains is charred and highly fragile.

Originally the missal probably comprised some 175 folios, of which 63 survive.

The script suggests a mid-to-late fourteenth century date, and the surviving initials are similar to those of English manuscripts of the mid-fourteenth century. The inclusion of Relic Sunday on the Sunday after the feast of Thomas Becket points to a Sarum use after the year 1319.
In the calendar, a later hand has added St David and St Chad, which may have occurred after the upgrading of these saints in England in 1415; it is also possible that the missal was acquired by St David's parish during its fifteenth-century refurbishment, and these saints added at that time. References to the pope have been removed throughout, meaning the missal was still in public use at the time of Henry VIII's edict of 1539.

Parts of ten quires survive, most of which were originally eight folios. It is possible to estimate that some seven or eight quires are missing from the Temporale, and a similar number from the Sanctorale; thus what survives is approximately one-third of the original missal.

Most of the missal is not notated. However, there are two columns of chant for the liturgical reading of the genealogy at Epiphany, in a mode 3 formula; why this is written out, and few other chants, is not obvious. Similarly, St Anne is given a sequence written out in full; possibly this reflects the relative novelty of the feast of St Anne, which was given official status in a papal bull transmitted by the Archbishop of Canterbury in 1383.

https://fragmentarium.ms/view/page/F-xs16/

title: Cluj-Napoca, Biblioteca Academiei Române, BMV R.12
summary: Single leaf from an office for Ursula. Four-line red staves with square notation. Lombard initials in blue and red; text in Northern texualis. Measures 340 x 490 mm with a written area of 350x 240mm; heavily trimmed for use in binding.
description: The single bifolio was formerly the centre of a quire of an antiphoner; thus the text runs continuously across all four pages. It contains a partial office for St Ursula: see Analecta Hymnica, v.5 no. 88. The meter is derived from the office for St. Dominic, "Gaude felix parens Hispania;" this office may have originated among the Dominicans of Cologne.
selected_bibliography: Analecta hymnica medii aevi, V: Lateinische Hymnendichter Mittelalters. Ed. C. Blume and G. M. Dreves. Leipzig, 1889. Quijano, César. "Antiphonale (a.u. Eccl. Coloniensis?) (Fragment)." Cluj-Napoca, Biblioteca Academiei Române, BMV R.12, wrapper. https://fragmentarium.ms/description/F-ryor/3882.

title: Umeå, University Library, Ink. 4
summary:
An in situ bifolio only visible on one side, binding an incunabula. 
Holding institution: Umeå University Library, Sweden
Shelfmark: Ink. 4
Binding of Aurelius Augustinus, Opuscula (Strassburg: Martin Flach, 1491).
Previous owners: N. M. H. F. (?) ; Olof Östergren (1874-1963)
Olof Östergren, according to his catalogue, bought the volume from the book dealer Richard du Rietz.
Dimensions are 280x200 mm
description: A bifolium containing mass chants for Septuagesima and Quinquagesima.

title: Umeå, University Library, Östergren F 00648: 1-3
summary:
Two leaves (or a bifolium?) forming a binding for early-modern print books. In situ (so versos are not visible). 

Holding institution: Umeå University Library, Sweden
Shelfmark: Östergren F 00648: 1-3
Sammelband containing three titles: 1. ”Liber Iudicum homiliis cvii” by Ludwig Lavater (Zürich, 1585); 2. “Galli Genealogia et chronologia sanctorum partum” (Basel, 1592); 3. “Sermones 30 in 11. caput Epistolæ ad Hebræos” by Huldrych Zwingli (Basel, 1592).
Previous owners: Jacobi Hessi 1792 ; W. Jackson (exlibris); Olof Östergren (1874-1963)
Olof Östergren, according to his catalogue, bought the volume from Harrassowitz (i.e. probably the bookseller and antiquarian Harrassowitz in Leipzig, Germany).

327x 210mm
description: Responsories from matins of Maundy Thursday and Good Friday
indexing_notes: Positions in the office are taken from the Cantus Analysis Tool.

title: College Park (USA), University of Maryland - Michelle Smith Performing Arts Library, s.n.
summary: Single parchment leaf from a gradual; probably Spanish, 1500-1550. 533 x 362 mm; writing area 430 x 260 mm.
liturgical_occasions: St Thomas of Canterbury; Sunday in Octave of Christmas
description:
Description courtesty of Barbara Haggh-Huglo, 2024, using information supplied by the donor. 
Deposited 31 May 2024 at University of Maryland in College Park in the Michelle Smith Performing Arts Library, Lowens Room (Special Collections).
One parchment leaf in good condition with wear only to the calligraphed initials from a probably Spanish gradual of the first half of the sixteenth century (1500-1550) beginning with the winter Temporale. Owned by Mark Hill’s father, D. E. Hill, and inherited by Mark Hill.
Contents: chant of end of offertory and communion for feast of St. Thomas of Canterbury, then chant of beginning of introit for Sunday in the octave of Christmas.
Measurements: leaf 53.3 x 36.2 cm with 6 red five-line staves per page made with a rastrum, and black square notation, with custodes. Recto side (hair side): writing surface 43 x 26 cm [distance between outer penciled lines 24.9 cm], stave height 4.5 cm. Verso (flesh) side: writing surface 43 x 25 cm [distance between outer penciled lines 26.5], stave height 4.7 cm. Two parallel penciled lines to right and left of writing surface. Two calligraphed initials on f. 38v.

Possible preceding gatherings:
• If gathering signature is a ‘C’ then 11 unnumbered leaves + A gathering of 12 leaves + B gathering of 12 leaves + first two leaves of C gathering, then this leaf. Would begins with introductory material – a title page, approval of bishop, calendar? Then gradual begins with first Sunday in Advent.
• [Most likely] If gathering signature is an ‘E’ then 3 unnumbered leaves + A B C D gatherings, each with 8 leaves + first two leaves of E gathering, then this leaf

title: Denton (USA), UNT College of Music Special Collections, D-03e8a
summary:
Single leaf of a gradual. Donated to the library in 2021 by UNT faculty who obtained it in Guatemala. 

450x345 mm 
writing area: 425x265 mm
description: Of Dominican origin. Contains the end of the communion for All Saints, followed by incipits for the octave, and then the introit for Theodore using an uncommon that is attested mostly in Spanish sources (in honour of Saturnius).
indexing_notes: We only received images of the recto, though the verso might be available from the library.

title: Denton (USA), UNT College of Music Special Collections, D-0aehq
summary:
This item was purchased by the University of North Texas Music Library. Sellers claim it is from an antiphoner in a Franciscan community in southern France, and gives a date of the late thirteenth century. 

405x300 mm
description: This leaf contains part of the hymn Pange lingua/crux fidelis for veneration of the cross on Good Friday. The verse Crux Fidelis/Dulce Lignum appears as a refrain. This practice is familiar to users of the Liber Usualis but is relatively uncommon in medieval sources.

title: Denton (USA), UNT College of Music Special Collections, D-0i04c
summary:
A leaf of antiphoner with several decorated initials. 

194x156 mm There is no donation record for this fragment in particular; it was likely part of a large collection which was donated to the library (Helen Hewitt or Lloyd Hibberd). 

Writing area 145x97mm
description: Contains a portion of vespers for the office of the dead. The format of the music is quite peculiar where at the beginning of the psalm there is an incipit for the antiphon followed by a differentia followed by the psalm written out in full. The complete antiphon is written at the end of the psalm.

title: Denton (USA), UNT College of Music Special Collections, D-0pkgx
summary:
A leaf of a neumated breviary, donated to UNT by Dr. Helen Hewitt. 
345x245mm 

writing area 285x190mm 

Only the recto was submitted. Is a binding fragment and the verso is likely badly damaged.
description: Contains the end of Matins and most of Lauds for Palm Sunday, including a number of processional antiphons.

title: Denton (USA), UNT College of Music Special Collections, D-0qcjh
summary:
Binding fragment on a copy of a book by Kepler. Digitized by the library with a description https://digital.library.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metadc1518451/
Provenance unknown, possibly from collections of Helen Hewitt or Lloyd Hibberd

448x324mm
description:
This is a book cover formed from two bifolios glued together. The first contains chants from September: a generic marian feast that is likely the Nativity of Mary, followed by Michael. The other side is still beneath its paste-downs, and is apparently visible under black-light. 

The second is a much smaller strip in the opposite orientation to the first. On the front cover, its contents are entirely beneath the early-modern title, but on the back cover, an Antiphon for Margaret is visible but in poor condition.

title: Kansas City (MO), University of Missouri-Kansas City - LaBudde Special Collections - Miller Nichols Library, MS 0285 Object 1
summary:
Sixteenth-seventeenth-century fragment out of an antiphoner from Spain. Five-line dry-point staves with F-clef, rastrum in red. Cursus unknown. 1 folio,  58 x 87 cm with a principal writing-space of 39.5 x 65 cm. Folio numbered in original hand "lxxvii" in red.

Ff. 1r-1v Dom. 2 post Pascha (likely); f. 1v Dom. 3 post Pascha.
description: Provenance of this fragment is unknown except for generally originating in Spain. It arrived at the LaBudde Special Collection in KC at some point, though there are no records of donor or purchase. There is difficulty in determining office and genres of the included chants more concretely than in studying chant concordances. Rubric for the Magnificat canticle on f. 1r suggests Vespers, though the chant that follows immediately appears to be a Responsory. Investigation of the subtle transfer from the previous folio to 1r may give more clues.

title: McClean (USA), Private Collection, D-00jf0
summary:
Single leaf from an Italian (?) gradual with chants for an unspecified bishop. 565 x 406mm. 
Writing area: side 1: 381 x 267; side 2: 419 x 267
description:
Single leaf from an Italian gradual. Purchased at auction in 2018 through Amherst Early Music. 
565 x 406mm. Writing area: side 1: 381 x 267; side 2: 419 x 267 (six staves on one side, seven on the other). Labeled CXXI on verso. Square notation on red four-line staff. Custos very pale, mostly downward-pointing, though sometimes with hairline tails seeming to extend in both directions (!). Script is Southern Textualis with hairline flourishes and slightly uneven minims; likely Italian, and perhaps 15th century or later.

There are no rubrications because the first half-word of the introit is on a previous leaf. This introit is in the Graduale Romanum for Jesus Votive Masses, and there is a single example of the Introit (without its verse) for Chair of St. Peter, though with a different gradual. The gradual is from the common of bishop. Absent rubrics, chants have been assigned to the common of bishops.

title: London (Ontario), Private collections, D-01oko
provenance_notes: Purchased from a vendor at a travelling Christmas bazaar in San Diego, California in the 1970s for $20 USD.
summary: Single parchment leaf from a gradual. Black square notation on four-line red staves with F- and C-clefs. 5 staves per folio side. Paper paste-overs cover sections of the original melody on the recto side. Rounded, humanistic script. Minimally-decorated initials alternating in blue and red inks. 409 x 307 mm, with a principal writing-space of 309 x 206 mm.
liturgical_occasions: 3 chants, likely from Comm. unius Martyris
description:
Rubrics, in red ink for an Offertory and a Communion, reveal that this leaf was from a gradual containing the sung liturgy for the Mass. Four paper paste-overs are affixed to staves on the recto side (which has the number '75' in the upper right-hand corner). These paper paste-overs cover sections of the melody, presumably simplifying the chants and reflecting melodic changes, possibly post-Council of Trent. There are no obvious changes to the texts. The ink has eaten away the paper leaving square-shaped holes, but the parchment is not showing signs of damage.

The recto side shows signs of glue residue on its edges; it may have been a pastedown at some point in its life.

Acquired for $20 USD by Dr. Heidi von Gunden from a vendor at a travelling Christmas bazaar in San Diego, California in the 1970s, and given to Dr. Alma Santosuosso (in London, Ontario) as a present in August of 1984. Currently in the private collection of A. Santosuosso (2024).
indexing_notes: The inventory for Cantus D:01oko (fragment) was entered by Debra Lacoste (Dalhousie University) and proofread by Anna de Bakker (Dalhousie University). Formerly CDN-LonONpc D-01oko (fragment).

title: North Vancouver (British Columbia), Private collections, D:02csu
summary: Single parchment leaf in private ownership. Square notation in black-brown ink on red 5-line staves, with F- and C-clefs. Use of custodes at the ends of the staves.
liturgical_occasions: Contains a sequence for the BVM.
description:
Single parchment leaf in a frame with both sides visible. Purchased at a book shop in Nurnberg in 1972; scant provenance information. Currently in private ownership in British Columbia, Canada.

Recto side is labeled CxCv = fol. 195r.

Each side has 7 lines of text in rotunda script with a narrow aspect, and square notation on 5-line red staves. The "G" at the start of each verse alternates red and blue, with the first being more decorated. Fol. 195r has additional decoration of swirls and flowers in blue and gold in the left and top margin.

The text is a sequence on the Joys of the Virgin, set to a variant of "Veni Sancte Spiritus." Two distinctive variants in the sequence text are: "Gaude quia oblatio...filio" and "Gaude quia paraclitus...collegio."
selected_bibliography: • Fragmentarium link: https://fragmentarium.ms/view/page/F-2csu
indexing_notes: The inventory for Cantus D:02csu (fragment) was entered by Anna de Bakker (Dalhousie University) and proofread by Debra Lacoste (Dalhousie University). Formerly CDN-NVanBCpc D-02csu (fragment).
indexing_date: Fall 2020; proofread in January 2024.

title: Halifax (Canada), Private collections, D-02fkm
summary: Single folio with chants for Corpus Christi.
description:
Single folio on vellum, numbered lxxxiii in upper right, containing chants "in festo corporis x(rist)i".
Five line red staves, square notation. Folio measures 575 x 393 mm; writing area 425 x 250 mm (recto) and 430 x 270 mm (verso). 
Acquired by current owner in 2017; previously privately owned, also in Halifax, and appraised there in 1998.

Script is Southern Textualis, with many prescissa minims (m, n), an h descending below the line, and r with a foot, all late Iberian features.

Words occasionally divided somewhat idiosyncratically ("pignu----s").  Music and text poorly aligned; text seems to have been written first, and sometimes syllable boundaries are not obvious from the neumes. Text is punctuated with colons and semicolons; the music has lines of division at these points. Corrections of various neumes visible, particularly on the recto, though these efforts apparently did not extend to either text alignment or the unusual ending of the Magnificat antiphon. Differentia given is also either unattested or in error. 

Somewhat unusual ordering of chants, as "Sicut novelle" is in the octave rather than first vespers of the feast. 

https://fragmentarium.ms/view/page/F-2fkm

title: Montreal (Quebec), Private collections, D-02ryf
summary: Single (framed) leaf from a print antiphoner, measuring 40.7 x 25.5 cm; writing area 36.0 x 21.1 cm. Five line moveable type staff with Hufnagel notation.
description:
Single (framed) leaf from a print antiphoner, measuring 40.7 x 25.5 cm; writing area 36.0 x 21.1 cm. Numbered CXXXI in upper right. Five line moveable type staff with Hufnagel notation, both in black; red used for initials and rubrics.  Uses both c and f clef (the latter with a zigzag shape), many diagonal dividing lines between words, and a distinctive four-line symbol at the conclusion of the first chant. 

Part of a series of chant volumes ("Canto Gregoriano Mogutinus") published in Mainz by Küchler from 1665-1667; this is (likely) the Hebdomedarium, vol.1.

Probably obtained in Germany (or Austria) between 1970-2000 but details are unknown.

Chants for a single confessor non pont. The melody of the invitatory resembles that used in some sources (e.g. D Aug. LX) for saints in Paschaltide, but without the Alleluia in the text, thus creating an opening melisma.

title: New York (USA), Private collections, D-03cfi
summary: Single leaf from a gradual.
description:
Single leaf from a gradual with chants for Marian votive masses. 
Measures approximately 546 x 381 mm  [writing area 445 x  267 mm]. 
Southern Textualis, possibly Spanish. Foliated cxxxv.
Very long-tailed custodes, which do not stay inside the margins. Occasional lines of division in the music. Characteristic syllable division (genitri-x). Caudas on e.
Melody for Felix namque suggests a Cistercian or Dominican origin.

title: Cincinnati (Ohio), Private collections, D-05k5s
summary: Page containing hymns from a fragmented liturgical book
description:
Single folio containing two melodies for the hymn "Creator alme siderum". The text post-dates Urban VIII's revisions (1631). 
The ferial melody may be a variant on mSTA126.

Measures 710 x 500 mm; writing are 620 x 390 mm on one side and 650 x 390 mm on the other. Script is Southern textualis prescissa (Spanish?).  Red and blue decorated initials mark the beginning of each verse, with slightly more elaborate initials beginning the first verse.

Musical notation is square neumes on a red five-line staff, of which there are six per page. Clefs are made of three lozenges; custodes are narrow with long, upward pointing tails. A sharp marks b-natural. In addition to virgae and puncta, lozenge shapes are also present, as well as an upward-pointing stem. Faint lines of division mark the end of each line. 

Layout is somewhat peculiar: the recto contains only the opening of the ferial melody, while the verso contains the text of the remaining verse rather than the continued melody. 

Inherited by the present owner from a family member; purchased at least prior to the 1940s. 

https://fragmentarium.ms/view/page/F-5k5s

description:
Single page from a breviary, probably German, with antiphons and readings for the second week after Easter.  Currently measures 248 x 184 mm; a note on frame suggests it may be 270 x 200 mm unframed.
Written area 211 x 155 mm, 24 lines.
Red, rounded initials with red lines.
Unheightened German-style neumes in a darker ink than main text and fairly thick.
Wormhole damage in margin, a vertical fold, and some other visible text suggests it may have been used in a binding.  

Obtained at Keys Auctioneers and Valuers, Norfolk, UK, 2020.

title: New York (USA), Private collections, D-06g6c
summary: Framed folio from an antiphoner, likely Franciscan.
description:
Single page from an antiphoner (opposite side is not visible.)
Approximately 483 x 349 mm; writing area takes up most of the vertical height and is about 265 mm wide. A thin red border surrounds the page.
Southern Textualis prescissus; square neumes on a five line red staff. 

Contains chants for Saturday or Sunday "per annum." 

The combination of the Magnificat antiphon "Suscepit deus" with the versicle Vespertina oratio strongly suggests a Franciscan source. The textual hand could be Spanish, but "Suscepit Deus" is more common in Italian sources. Late; perhaps 16th or 17th century.

title: Hartford (CT), Private collections, D-0777g
summary: Single leaf from a Franciscan antiphoner
description:
https://fragmentarium.ms/overview/F-777g

Donated to the Hartt School or the University of Hartford by Rabbi Abraham J Feldman, DD, per information on the frame of the fragment. Feldman was rabbi at congregation Beth Israel from 1925-1968 and received an honorary degree from the Hartt School in 1953.

Area: 492x 368 mm; writing area 406x 263.5 mm. Southern textualis script (likely Italian). Four-line staff, six per page. Blue and red puzzle initials on both sides of the leaf.


Numbered CLXVIII in upper right in an early modern hand.

title: Connecticut USA, Private collections, D-07e7c
summary: Six fragments from an antiphoner leaf used in the spine of an 18th-century book binding, probably from the early-thirteenth century, with square notation on grey/black four-line staves. Cistercian.
description:
This reconstructed parchment leaf contains several fragments that are part of a series of musical binding materials ("The Ridgefield Project"). The parchment was used to bind volumes of the "Histoire Ecclésiastique pour servir de continuation à celle de Monsieur l'Abbé Fleury" (Paris, Pierre-Jean Mariette, 1722-1738). This partial folio, composed of 6 “ladder” pieces ("Group D”) from Volumes 1, 7, and 28 of the Histoire (1722, 1727, 1730), is from the antiphoner, and contains chants for the first Sunday in Advent.

Text hand is praegothica (likely s.13, first half), with curved feet and occasional S and T ligatures (even when the letters are physically separated, the curve is present.) Musical notation is square on a grey/black, four-line staff. Staff height between 12.5 and 14.5 mm. Most notes have a rightward lean, with a stem poking up on the upper right of the note. Connected neumes often have a somewhat curved oblique stroke, with varying thickness. B-flat is present, with a fork in the stem. Both f and c clefs are used, depending on the mode of the chant. The scandicus is sometimes stacked four high. The climacus sometimes has a stem on the left.

The notation suggests a Cistercian provenance, which is in general corroborated by the Cistercian usage suggested by the remaining contents. However, nothing is known about the provenance prior to its use as a binding fragment.

More on the Ridgefield Fragments may be found in the description for Group F
indexing_notes: This item was contributed by the Ridgefield Fragments Project; a private collection of over 100 pieces of musical and textual manuscript recovered from the spines of 25 18th century French books during restoration. The owner, who may be contacted via email at  RidgefieldFragments@gmail.com, expresses his thanks for the support of the DACT team and wider academic community.

title: Connecticut USA, Private collections, D-07lvz
summary: Six parchment fragments comprising approximately half a leaf of an antiphoner, probably from the early-thirteenth century, used in eighteenth-century book bindings. Possibly Cistercian. Square notation on a black four-line staff.
description:
This reconstructed parchment leaf is composed of six fragments that are part of a series of musical binding materials ("The Ridgefield Project"). The parchment was used to bind volumes of the "Histoire Ecclesiastique pour servir de continuation à celle de Monsieur l'Abbé Fleury" (Paris, Pierre-Jean Mariette, 1720-1730). (See https://cantusdatabase.org/source/714555).

The parchment pieces found in the Ridgefield Project appear to be from a thirteenth-century antiphoner and gradual from an (as yet unidentified) Cistercian monastery, possibly in France or Belgium. This half folio is composed of six binding pieces ("Group C") from Volumes 15, 17, and 21 of the Histoire, and is from an antiphoner. The chants are for the feast of Agatha; it is likely this folio was near "Group B" (perhaps even as part of a bifolio).
selected_bibliography: Cistercian antiphoner (Fragment), Utopia, armarium codicum bibliophilorum (https://fragmentarium.ms/overview/F-7lvz)
indexing_notes: The fragments in Connecticut USA, Private collections, D-07lvz were inventoried by Anna de Bakker (Dalhousie University) and proofread by Debra Lacoste (Dalhousie University). This item was contributed by the Ridgefield Fragments Project; a private collection of over 100 pieces of musical and textual manuscript recovered from the spines of 25 18th century French books during restoration. The owner, who may be contacted via email at  RidgefieldFragments@gmail.com, expresses his thanks for the support of the DACT team and wider academic community.
indexing_date: Indexed in Fall 2023, published online Nov 3, 2023.

title: Oxford (UK), Private collections, D-083py

title: Connecticut USA, Private collections, D-0b3z1
summary: Five parchment fragments comprising approximately half a leaf from a gradual, probably from the late-thirteenth century, used in eighteenth-century book bindings. Possibly Cistercian. Square notation on a red four-line staff.  Current area is approximately 200x125 mm, with each individual piece approximately 63 mm on each side.
description:
This reconstructed parchment leaf is composed of five fragments that are part of a series of musical binding materials ("The Ridgefield Project"). The parchment was used to bind volumes of the "Histoire Ecclesiastique pour servir de continuation à celle de Monsieur l'Abbé Fleury" (Paris, Pierre-Jean Mariette, 1720-1730). (See https://cantusdatabase.org/source/714555.) This half folio is composed of several binding pieces ("Group A") from Volumes 11, 14, and 22 of the Histoire, published in 1720, 1726, and 1727).

Together, the fragments form approximately half a folio from a gradual, likely dating from the thirteenth century. One portion contains chants apparently for a Marian votive mass; the other gives incipits for a series of other votive masses. The listed votive masses, the chants used, and even the relative locations of the chants referenced within the volume, are all consistent with Cistercian sources, suggesting the same provenance as the antiphoner fragments used in the same bindings.
Current area is approximately 200x125 mm, with each individual piece approximately 63 mm on each side. Based on other pieces, the original dimensions of the page were likely ~230-250 mm across, but the height has not yet been established.

The fragments from the Ridgefield Project are:
Group A (Gradual): https://fragmentarium.ms/overview/F-b3z1 https://cantusdatabase.org/source/1000008
Group B (Antiphoner): https://fragmentarium.ms/overview/F-e78r https://cantusdatabase.org/source/1000006
Group C (Antiphoner): https://fragmentarium.ms/overview/F-7lvz https://cantusdatabase.org/source/1000007
Group D (Antiphoner): https://fragmentarium.ms/overview/F-7e7c (not yet published on Fragmentarium) https://cantusdatabase.org/source/1000009
Group E (Antiphoner): https://fragmentarium.ms/overview/F-ly13 (not yet published on Fragmentarium) https://cantusdatabase.org/source/1000010
Group F (Antiphoner): https://fragmentarium.ms/overview/F-yp1h https://cantusdatabase.org/source/714555
Group G (Antiphoner): https://fragmentarium.ms/view/page/F-k0iy https://cantusdatabase.org/source/1000027 Group H (Antiphoner): https://fragmentarium.ms/view/page/F-f4dd https://cantusdatabase.org/source/1000028 Group I (Antiphoner): https://fragmentarium.ms/view/page/F-jb34 https://cantusdatabase.org/source/1000029 Group J (Antiphoner): https://fragmentarium.ms/view/page/F-ciuc (No chant contents) Group K (Antiphoner): https://fragmentarium.ms/view/page/F-vyii https://cantusdatabase.org/source/1000030 Groups L-O, from the Gradual, are yet to be published on Fragmentarium. In addition, several other fragments possibly pertaining to the same institution(s) were part of the same bindings. https://fragmentarium.ms/view/page/F-036q appears to be a 17th century table of contents or reading, while the many fragments of https://fragmentarium.ms/view/page/F-rv55 have not yet been identified.
selected_bibliography: Fragmentarium: Gradual (Cistercian) (Fragment), Utopia, armarium codicum bibliophilorum (https://fragmentarium.ms/overview/F-b3z1)
indexing_notes: The fragments in Connecticut USA, Private collections, D-0b3z1 were inventoried by Anna de Bakker (Dalhousie University) and proofread by Debra Lacoste (Dalhousie University). This item was contributed by the Ridgefield Fragments Project, a private collection of over 100 pieces of musical and textual manuscript recovered during restoration from the spines of 25 18th-century French books. The owner, who may be contacted via email at  RidgefieldFragments@gmail.com, expresses his thanks for the support of the DACT team and wider academic community.
indexing_date: Inventoried in spring and summer of 2023. Published online in late 2023.

title: Montreal (Quebec), Private collections, D-0dex0
summary: Two leaves from a (probably secular-cursus) antiphoner containing chants for John the Baptist and Peter&Paul. Page dimensions, 560x390mm; written area approx. 410 x 255 mm.
description:
Two fragments, likely from the same manuscript, obtained in Paris in August 1930, according to a note on the back of the frame. 
Page dimensions, 560x390mm; written area approx. 410 x 255 mm.
Southern Textualis (perhaps French?).
Red, four-line staff, five per page; upward pointing custodes, and red divisio lines.
Initials one line in height, open each antiphon, alternating red on a blue background and a somewhat brighter blue on a red background, both with penwork. Second letters of antiphons and opening letters of psalms highlighted in a now-faded yellow. Narrow, slightly curved c-clefs; f clef with three downward pointing rectangles. A catchword, "quando," on 1v. 


https://fragmentarium.ms/view/page/F-dex0/5732/52800

title: Connecticut USA, Private collections, D-0e78r
summary: Four parchment fragments comprising approximately half a leaf from an antiphoner, probably from the early-thirteenth century, used in eighteenth-century book bindings. Possibly Cistercian. Square notation on a black four-line staff.
description:
This reconstructed parchment leaf contains four fragments that are part of a series of musical binding materials ("The Ridgefield Project"). The parchment was used to bind volumes of the "Histoire Ecclesiastique pour servir de continuation à celle de Monsieur l'Abbé Fleury" (Paris, Pierre-Jean Mariette, 1720-1730). (See https://cantusdatabase.org/source/714555.)

The parchment pieces found in the Ridgefield Project appear to be from a thirteenth-century antiphoner and gradual, both from an (as yet unidentified) Cistercian monastery, possibly in France or Belgium. This half folio, composed of four binding pieces ("Group B") from Volumes 14 and 22 of the Histoire, is from the antiphoner, and contains chants for Matins on the feast of Agatha.
selected_bibliography: Fragmentarium: Cistercian antiphoner (Fragment), Ridgefield, CT, Private collection (https://fragmentarium.ms/overview/F-e78r)
indexing_notes: The fragments in Connecticut USA, Private collections, D-0e78r were inventoried by Anna de Bakker (Dalhousie University) and proofread by Debra Lacoste (Dalhousie University).This item was contributed by the Ridgefield Fragments Project, a private collection of over 100 pieces of musical and textual manuscript recovered during restoration from the spines of 25 18th-century French books. The owner, who may be contacted via email at  RidgefieldFragments@gmail.com, expresses his thanks for the support of the DACT team and wider academic community.
indexing_date: Indexed in Fall 2023, published online Nov 3, 2023.

title: Porto Alegre (Brazil), Private collections, D-0egev
description:
Single leaf from an illuminated antiphoner. Current owner inherited it from an acquaintance (also in Brazil) who likely acquired it in Germany, at least a few decades ago (though it may have been in the family even longer.) 
Four line staff in red, with square notation; c-clef is formed of two lozenges, while the f-clef has four strokes, two horizontal and two diagonal. 
The script appears, based on Derolez, to be a late fifteenth-century German style of Fractura; some evidence of Hybrida in the hand used for rubricating. 
Leaf is apparently numbered ii.cc.xvii on upper right
An initial with red and blue flowers with leafy stems on a  speckled yellow background, surrounded by gold, appears for the invitatory chant; the inner margin of the page has a matching style, with red and pale yellow flowers and blue curlicues on a speckled ribbon. 
Other initials are inside rectangles, with red and blue backgrounds and faces in black ink. 

35 cm x 49 cm ; writing area 27 x 37 cm .

title: Bristol (UK), Private collections, D-0eqhg
description:
Single leaf from a gradual, thought to have been purchased around 1940-1945 at the Portobello market in London.  Currently framed and only one side is visible. Some fading/deterioration of ink has occurred through storage. Foliated CXLVIII on upper right.
Measures 510x355 mm, with a written area of 430x280 mm.

Musical notation:
9 staves per page. Each staff is four red lines. F clefs are three oblong marks with a long "descender"; c-clefs occasionally also appear, and are  formed of two narrow, slightly angled rectangles.  Square neumes, quite large, frequently touching. 

Script/decoration:
A red-and-blue I "puzzle initial" with considerable red filigree,  two staff-lines in height, begins the introit. A 'ribbon-like' initial in black begins the introit verse. Text is written in a Gothic script with very few hairlines and a few distinguishing characteristics: long s lacks feet or a spur,  g has a small lower loop and a connecting 'hook'. Although the text is narrow and angular, the ascender on d is horizontal (usually a southern feature), and the a is open. Dating and provenance is thus difficult to establish. 

Usage:
There is evidence of some correction of the manuscript: two page references for incipits were erased and changed (lxviii to lxxviii) and the numbering of the relevant Sunday apparently changed (from xx?) to "x9", with "19" in the margin. This suggests the changes were made fairly late, when Arabic numerals had become the norm; it may also point to the rite used, as the chants are more typically for the 21st and not the 19th Sunday after Pentecost.

Single leaf from a gradual, thought to have been purchased around 1940-1945 at the Portobello market in London. Currently framed and only one side is visible. Some fading/deterioration of ink has occurred through storage. Foliated CXLVIII on upper right.
Measures 510x355 mm, with a written area of 430x280 mm.

Musical notation:
9 staves per page. Each staff is four red lines. F clefs are three oblong marks with a long "descender"; c-clefs occasionally also appear, and are formed of two narrow, slightly angled rectangles. Square neumes, quite large, frequently touching.

title: Victoria (British Columbia), Private collection, D-0es6l
summary: Single leaf containing part of the Tract and Litany for Easter Vigil. 520 x 375 mm; writing area 410 x 265 mm.
description:
Single leaf containing part of the Tract and Litany for Easter Vigil. 520 x 375 mm; writing area 410 x 265 mm.
Square notation in black ink on a red five-line staff.  Faint lines of division. Downward custodes.
Labelled "cv" in roman numerals, and "105" in Arabic numerals (partially cut off due to trimming).

Although a five-line staff is often taken to be suggestive of Spain, the textual hand seems firmly northern in its angularity. There is one long (one staff tall) red initial, opening the litany, and two elongated initials in black with double lines and sawtooth decorations opening the tract verses.  Other litany verses have small lombards alternating red and blue. 
Other distinctive features include the tendency to distance the final consonant from the vowel (vi-vu--m) and the setting of the names "Raphael", "Michael" with the accent on the final syllable. 
There are several errors present: the ending of two tract verses is apparently miscopied in two different ways, "Christelyson" has an "e" missing, and one of the litany's lombards is the wrong letter.

title: Rottenburg (Germany), Private collections, D-0f2cr
summary: Single page from an antiphoner containing chants for St Francis. 586 x 382 mm ; writing area 426 x 255 mm.
description:
Single page from an antiphoner containing chants for St Francis. 586 x 382 mm ; writing area 426 x 255 mm. Script is Southern Textualis Praescissa. Five-line red staff, square notation; f-clefs are made of three lozenges, and custodes are at a  45-degree angle with upward tails. Very faint lines of division present. First antiphon of Lauds has an initial in blue and red; the second has black penwork. Overall appearance suggests a possible Spanish origin, though the fragment was purchased in Paris.  There are insufficient chants present to determine the cursus.

title: Connecticut USA, Private collections, D-0f4dd
summary: Five small fragments from an antiphoner leaf used in the spine of an 18th-century book binding, probably from the early thirteenth century, with square notation on grey/black four-line staves. Cistercian.
description:
This reconstructed partial parchment leaf contains several fragments that are part of a series of musical binding materials ("The Ridgefield Project"). The parchment was used to bind volumes of the "Histoire Ecclésiastique pour servir de continuation à celle de Monsieur l'Abbé Fleury" (Paris, Pierre-Jean Mariette, 1722-1738). This small fragment, composed of 5 “head/tail” pieces ("Group H”) from Volumes 10, 12, 16 and 32 of the Histoire (1728, 1706, 1729, 1733), is from the antiphoner, and contains chants for the Sunday in the Octave of Christmas and (on the verso) Epiphany. Text hand is praegothica (likely s.13, first half), with curved feet and occasional S and T ligatures (even when the letters are physically separated, the curve is present.) Musical notation is square on a grey/black, four-line staff. Staff height between 12.5 and 14.5 mm. Most notes have a rightward lean, with a stem poking up on the upper right of the note. Connected neumes often have a somewhat curved oblique stroke, with varying thickness. B-flat is present, with a fork in the stem. Both f and c clefs are used, depending on the mode of the chant. The scandicus is sometimes stacked four high. The climacus sometimes has a stem on the left.
The notation suggests a Cistercian provenance, which is in general corroborated by the Cistercian usage suggested by the remaining contents. However, nothing is known about the provenance prior to its use as a binding fragment.
More on the Ridgefield Fragments may be found in the description for Group F.

title: Salem (New Hampshire), Private collections, D-0fery
summary: Single leaf from a sequentiary.
description:
Single leaf from a chant manuscript, purchased at an antique shop in Tuscany in 2006. Rubric in Italian: "sequenza del corpus christi"; Italian spelling of "hinis" for "hymnis". 
Text in a late, Italian textualis;  probably by two scribes as there are two very distinctive g-shapes, and two slightly different forms for "p" as well. "U" , and on occasion "n", has a foot going below the line, and final "s" is the "long" form more characteristic of rapid scripts.  Red and blue decoration on initials, which is more elaborate on the L beginning Lauda Sion. 

Numbered "36" in upper right, suggesting the leaf was once near the beginning of a sequentiary rather than the back of a gradual. 

Square notation on a red 4-line staff, rather thick, 6 per page. Custodes present; c-clef is narrow and rectangular with a slightly extended lower stroke. Light dividing lines mark phrases within each sequence, which do not necessarily coincide with poetic lines. 
Some evidence of errors and correction in several places. Several accidentals present. "Amen alleluia" concluding "Veni sancte spiritus" might be melodically distinctive.

title: New York (USA), Private collections, D-0ghwf
summary: Single page of a gradual.
description:
Single page of a gradual; foliated "l" in upper right. Chant for votive masses "pro vitanda mortalitate " (probably the "Recordare domine" mass purportedly compiled during the Black Death.)
No provenance information was given. The text (southern textualis praescissus)  and music notation (five-line staff) suggest a Spanish origin, but do not prove it.  Cedillas on e; spaced- out syllables (sum-u-s.)
Folio is approximately 540 x 375 mm  [writing area 467 x 267mm]. The writing area is marked by a two line border, probably in drypoint; the name of the mass is given in red on the upper border, and the clefs and custodes are written within the vertical border. 


https://fragmentarium.ms//F-ghwf

title: Connecticut USA, Private collections, D-0gpiu
summary: Six parchment fragments rom a gradual, probably from the late-thirteenth century, used in eighteenth-century book bindings. Possibly Cistercian. Square notation on a red four-line staff. Each smaller strip measures approximately 30 x 60 mm; together, four of them make a strip of  30x 230 mm (the width of the page).
description:
PLACEHOLDER--Group L

This reconstructed section of a parchment leaf is composed of six fragments that are part of a series of musical binding materials ("The Ridgefield Project"). The parchment was used to bind volumes of the "Histoire Ecclesiastique pour servir de continuation à celle de Monsieur l'Abbé Fleury" (Paris, Pierre-Jean Mariette, 1720-1730). (See https://cantusdatabase.org/source/714555.) This partial folio is composed of several binding pieces ("Group L") from Volumes 15, 17, and 23 of the Histoire, published in 1719, 1727, and 1730.

The gradual likely dates from the thirteenth century. Other pieces used in the same binding suggest a Cistercian usage; possibly the antiphoner used in the same bindings had the same provenance. 

Current area is an irregular shape,  approximately 60 x 230 mm. From this reconstruction it may be established that the original dimensions of the page were likely ~230 mm across, but the height has not yet been established.
indexing_notes: The fragments in Connecticut USA, Private collections, D-0b3z1 were inventoried by Anna de Bakker (Dalhousie University) and proofread by Debra Lacoste (Dalhousie University). This item was contributed by the Ridgefield Fragments Project, a private collection of over 100 pieces of musical and textual manuscript recovered during restoration from the spines of 25 18th-century French books. The owner, who may be contacted via email at RidgefieldFragments@gmail.com, expresses his thanks for the support of the DACT team and wider academic community.

summary: Fragmented leaf from an antiphoner. Sixteenth century (?).
description:
Single leaf from an antiphoner. Square notation in black ink on red five-line staves with F- and C-clefs; 6 lines per folio side. Rounded textual script suggests the sixteenth century or later. 50.5 x 37.5 cm, with a principal writing space of 37.2 x 24.5 cm. Acquired at an estate sale in California, USA. Currently in the private collection of S. Helak (2018).

title: Connecticut USA, Private collections, D-0jb34
summary: Three small fragments from an antiphoner leaf used in the spine of an 18th-century book binding, probably from the early thirteenth century, with square notation on grey/black four-line staves. Cistercian.
description:
This reconstructed partial parchment leaf contains several fragments that are part of a series of musical binding materials ("The Ridgefield Project"). The parchment was used to bind volumes of the "Histoire Ecclésiastique pour servir de continuation à celle de Monsieur l'Abbé Fleury" (Paris, Pierre-Jean Mariette, 1722-1738). This small fragment, composed of 3 “head/tail” pieces ("Group I”) from Volumes 31 and 32 of the Histoire (1732/1733), is from the antiphoner, and contains chants for the Sunday in the Octave of Christmas. It appears to be from the same folio as Group H. Text hand is praegothica (likely s.13, first half), with curved feet and occasional S and T ligatures (even when the letters are physically separated, the curve is present.) Musical notation is square on a grey/black, four-line staff. Staff height between 12.5 and 14.5 mm. Most notes have a rightward lean, with a stem poking up on the upper right of the note. Connected neumes often have a somewhat curved oblique stroke, with varying thickness. B-flat is present, with a fork in the stem. Both f and c clefs are used, depending on the mode of the chant. The scandicus is sometimes stacked four high. The climacus sometimes has a stem on the left.
The notation suggests a Cistercian provenance, which is in general corroborated by the Cistercian usage suggested by the remaining contents. However, nothing is known about the provenance prior to its use as a binding fragment.
More on the Ridgefield Fragments may be found in the description for Group F.

title: Connecticut USA, Private collections, D-0k0iy
summary: Four fragments from an antiphoner leaf used in the spine of an 18th-century book binding, probably from the early thirteenth century, with square notation on grey/black four-line staves. Cistercian.
description:
This reconstructed parchment leaf contains several fragments that are part of a series of musical binding materials ("The Ridgefield Project"). The parchment was used to bind volumes of the "Histoire Ecclésiastique pour servir de continuation à celle de Monsieur l'Abbé Fleury" (Paris, Pierre-Jean Mariette, 1722-1738). This half folio, composed of 4 “ladder” pieces ("Group G”) from Volumes 9 and 27 of the Histoire (1720, 1730), is from the antiphoner, and contains chants for the fourth Sunday in Lent. Text hand is praegothica (likely s.13, first half), with curved feet and occasional S and T ligatures (even when the letters are physically separated, the curve is present.) Musical notation is square on a grey/black, four-line staff. Staff height between 12.5 and 14.5 mm. Most notes have a rightward lean, with a stem poking up on the upper right of the note. Connected neumes often have a somewhat curved oblique stroke, with varying thickness. B-flat is present, with a fork in the stem. Both f and c clefs are used, depending on the mode of the chant. The scandicus is sometimes stacked four high. The climacus sometimes has a stem on the left.
The notation suggests a Cistercian provenance, which is in general corroborated by the Cistercian usage suggested by the remaining contents. However, nothing is known about the provenance prior to its use as a binding fragment.
More on the Ridgefield Fragments may be found in the description for Group F.

title: New York (USA), Private collections, D-0kmpp
description:
Purchased by the current owner at the New York International Antiquarian Book Fair. The seller relayed that the leaves for sale were bought on auction, likely in Europe. Decorative motifs on other leafs in the same collection led the auction house to localize the manuscript to Italy, perhaps Verona or Mantua. The style of initials and the texts of the chants are also similar to manuscripts from northern Italy.
Dated by the auction house to ca. 1470.

Fragmentarium entry: https://fragmentarium.ms/view/page/F-kmpp

title: Connecticut USA, Private collections, D-0ksrz
summary: Two parchment fragments from a gradual, probably from the late-thirteenth century, used in eighteenth-century book bindings. Possibly Cistercian. Square notation on a red four-line staff. Two strips: one approximately 50 x 75 mm, the other 35 x 65 mm.
description:
PLACEHOLDER--Group O

This reconstructed section of a parchment leaf is composed of two fragments that are part of a series of musical binding materials ("The Ridgefield Project"). The parchment was used to bind volumes of the "Histoire Ecclesiastique pour servir de continuation à celle de Monsieur l'Abbé Fleury" (Paris, Pierre-Jean Mariette, 1720-1730). (See https://cantusdatabase.org/source/714555.) This partial folio is composed of several binding pieces ("Group O") from Volume 33 of the Histoire, published in 1734.

The gradual likely dates from the thirteenth century. Other pieces used in the same binding suggest a Cistercian usage; possibly the antiphoner used in the same bindings had the same provenance. 

Current area is an irregular shape approximately 85 x 110 mm. Based on other pieces, the original dimensions of the page were likely ~230-250 mm across, but the height has not yet been established.
indexing_notes: The fragments in Connecticut USA, Private collections, D-0b3z1 were inventoried by Anna de Bakker (Dalhousie University) and proofread by Debra Lacoste (Dalhousie University). This item was contributed by the Ridgefield Fragments Project, a private collection of over 100 pieces of musical and textual manuscript recovered during restoration from the spines of 25 18th-century French books. The owner, who may be contacted via email at RidgefieldFragments@gmail.com, expresses his thanks for the support of the DACT team and wider academic community.

title: Newcastle (South Africa), Private collections, D-0luvn
summary: Leaf from an antiphoner, 360 x 480 mm, with chants for Christmas.
description:
Leaf from an antiphoner, unknown provenance. Bought at auction in South Africa in spring 2024. Foliated as "13" at top of page in Arabic numerals, apparently contemporaneous with the chant.
Text and music hands suggest an Italian provenance, possibly 16th century or later. Square notation with use of diamond-shaped neumes.
The use of the versicle "Notum fecit" at Vespers is consistent with Italian and Franciscan sources.

title: Connecticut USA, Private collections, D-0ly13
summary: Two small parchment fragments from an antiphoner, probably from the early-thirteenth century, used in eighteenth-century book bindings. Possibly Cistercian. Square notation on a black four-line staff.
description:
This reconstructed fragment combines several smaller pieces that are part of a series of musical binding materials ("The Ridgefield Project"). The parchment was used to bind volumes of the "Histoire Ecclésiastique pour servir de continuation à celle de Monsieur l'Abbé Fleury" (Paris, Pierre-Jean Mariette, 1722-1738). This small fragment, composed of 2 head/tail pieces ("Group E”) from Volumes 1 and 7 of the Histoire (1722/1727), is from the antiphoner, and contains chants for the first Sunday in Advent.
Text hand is praegothica (likely s.13, first half), with curved feet and occasional S and T ligatures (even when the letters are physically separated, the curve is present.) Musical notation is square on a grey/black, four-line staff. Staff height between 12.5 and 14.5 mm. Most notes have a rightward lean, with a stem poking up on the upper right of the note. Connected neumes often have a somewhat curved oblique stroke, with varying thickness. B-flat is present, with a fork in the stem. Both f and c clefs are used, depending on the mode of the chant. The scandicus is sometimes stacked four high. The climacus sometimes has a stem on the left.

The notation suggests a Cistercian provenance, which is in general corroborated by the Cistercian usage suggested by the remaining contents. However, nothing is known about the provenance prior to its use as a binding fragment.
More on the Ridgefield Fragments may be found in the description for Group F.
indexing_notes: This item was contributed by the Ridgefield Fragments Project; a private collection of over 100 pieces of musical and textual manuscript recovered from the spines of 25 18th century French books during restoration. The owner, who may be contacted via email at  RidgefieldFragments@gmail.com, expresses his thanks for the support of the DACT team and wider academic community.

title: Issaquah (WA), Private collections, D-0p4kz
summary: Single leaf from an antiphoner, probably Spanish.
description:
Single leaf with unknown origin; purchased at a thrift shop (in 2020's) with little information. 
Measures  560 mm x 394mm; writing area 483 mm x 280 mm.  Numbered 48 in Arabic numerals in upper right, probably contemporaneous with the contents.
Script is Southern Textualis prescissa; some ascenders (e.g. s, b) have a single hook, and the "ae" digraph is a distinctive three-stroke shape. Most capitals are simple, red, and seemingly influenced by print-style Roman lettering. Five-line staff in red, with square neumes. 
Appearance suggests the fragment originated in Spain. The music is more elaborate than other versions of the antiphon presented (a specifically Spanish variant?)
The feast and placement is unknown, but the presence of the psalm may suggest it is not the typical use at the end of Lauds on Passion Sunday; Sext the following Monday seems likely.

title: Ashland (Oregon), Private collections, D-0pkms
summary: Single page, likely from an antiphoner, 468 x 348 mm. Writing area 368x 257. Several chants for Invention of Holy Cross.
description:
Single page, likely from an antiphoner, 468 x 348 mm. Writing area 368x 257. Several chants for Invention of Holy Cross (with Alleluias). 

Four line, red staves, seven per page.  Square notation with thin hairlines and lines of division; upward virgas. 
Text hand is a very precise southern textualis with some prescissa aspects; likely Italian, and 16th century or even later.

title: Los Angeles (USA), Private Collection, D-0poon
summary:
Fragment of a gradual 
Purchased in Spain in 1991
775 x 584 mm
description: Contains two alleluias which typically appear for apostles or evangelists.  P-Ln (Lisboa) Biblioteca Nacional de Portugal L.C. 243 has these two chants in sequence (with different melodies) with no rubrication, much like this fragment. Our source, which is also Iberian, is likely doing some sort of similar commons of apostles grab bag.

title: Kitchener (Ontario), Private collections, D:0uhiz
summary: Single parchment leaf from an antiphoner. Square notation in black ink on red four-line staves with F- and C-clefs; 7 lines per folio side. Rounded, southern textualis script. 507 x 389 mm, with a principal writing space of 386 x 285 mm.
liturgical_occasions: Nat. Innocentium; memorials for Thomae Apost. and Joannis Evang.; Dom. p. Nat. Dom. and Nativitas Domini,8
description:
The fragment is difficult to date. The script suggests the fifteenth century or later; there is also significant marginal decoration in a somewhat Baroque style. The manner in which the decoration intersects with the text gives the impression that the decoration was executed first, rather than being a later addition, and so the whole fragment may date to the early to mid eighteenth century. (There is some evidence that antiquarian, "medieval" style scripts were still in use in northern Italy as late as the 1730's; see for example https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/473907)

Acquired at an outdoor market in Florence, Italy. Currently in the private collection of D. Lacoste (2020).
indexing_notes: The inventory for Cantus D:0uhiz (fragment) was created by Anna de Bakker (Dalhousie University) and proofread by Debra Lacoste (Dalhousie University). Formerly CDN-WatONpc D-0uhiz (fragment). Formerly located in "Waterloo" (now Kitchener).
indexing_date: Indexed in Fall 2020; proofread and published 3 Feb 2024.

title: Eindhoven (Netherlands), Private collections, D-0v8wt
summary: Single leaf from a gradual.
description:
Single leaf from a gradual, used as a binding fragment and heavily trimmed. Chants for Trinity Sunday, Sundays after Pentecost.

Five line staff in red, with a small c and occasional f-clef (which appears as two dots) in a delineated margin. A similar margin is also present on the right and occasionally contains a custos. In its original state, probably 14 staves per page. Hufnagel-style notation. 

Pen trials of the line "Eins ist not ach Gott!" from a 1695 Lutheran devotional song attest to the fragment's presence (as a binding) in a German Protestant household in the 17th century.

title: Connecticut USA, Private collections, D-0vyii
summary: Two small parchment fragments from an antiphoner, probably from the early-thirteenth century, used in eighteenth-century book bindings. Possibly Cistercian. Square notation on a black four-line staff.
liturgical_occasions: Dom 5 p. Epiphaniae, Dom. per annum
description:
This reconstructed fragment combines several smaller pieces that are part of a series of musical binding materials ("The Ridgefield Project"). The parchment was used to bind volumes of the "Histoire Ecclésiastique pour servir de continuation à celle de Monsieur l'Abbé Fleury" (Paris, Pierre-Jean Mariette, 1722-1738). This small fragment, composed of 2 head/tail pieces ("Group K”) from Volumes 28 and 29 of the Histoire (1730), is from the antiphoner, and contains chants for the fifth Sunday after Epiphany and Sundays "per annum.
Text hand is praegothica (likely s.13, first half), with curved feet and occasional S and T ligatures (even when the letters are physically separated, the curve is present.) Musical notation is square on a grey/black, four-line staff. Staff height between 12.5 and 14.5 mm. Most notes have a rightward lean, with a stem poking up on the upper right of the note. Connected neumes often have a somewhat curved oblique stroke, with varying thickness. B-flat is present, with a fork in the stem. Both f and c clefs are used, depending on the mode of the chant. The scandicus is sometimes stacked four high. The climacus sometimes has a stem on the left.

The notation suggests a Cistercian provenance, which is in general corroborated by the Cistercian usage suggested by the remaining contents. However, nothing is known about the provenance prior to its use as a binding fragment.
More on the Ridgefield Fragments may be found in the description for Group F.
indexing_notes: This item was contributed by the Ridgefield Fragments Project; a private collection of over 100 pieces of musical and textual manuscript recovered from the spines of 25 18th century French books during restoration. The owner, who may be contacted via email at  RidgefieldFragments@gmail.com, expresses his thanks for the support of the DACT team and wider academic community.

title: Montreal (Quebec), Private collections, D-0xbns
summary: Single leaf from an antiphoner with table of contents and an added chant for Dom 2. post Pascha. 50.0 x 37.7 cm; writing area 38.0x 26.5 cm. Square notation on red four-line staff.
description:
Single leaf from an antiphoner with table of contents and an added chant for Dom 2. post Pascha. 50.0 x 37.7 cm; writing area 38.0x 26.5 cm.
Narrow vertical margins visible. Labeled 144 in upper right. Table of Contents suggests the volume only contained chants for the Temporale.
A late Gothic hand is visible at the top of the fragment, and on the verso; stenciled "print-like" letters are also present. The page has been repurposed and re-decorated at least once.
Four-line red staff (six per page). Two musical hands present. One has a slightly tilted c-clef and virga with thin descenders; the other uses curved c and f clefs, a rounded flat, and puncta that have hairlines on either side, as well as a small and angular custos.

 A figure of a nun in blue with a white wimple and holding a book sits inside a red E, which in turn is inside a gold square. A border of pink, blue, and purple bell-shaped flowers and their leaves curves into three sides of the page, with gold bezants.

Although likely purchased in Paris in the 1930s, certain factors (such as the spelling "alleluja" suggest a German or Dutch origin. 
The melody for "Ego sum pastor bonus," in mode 8, is somewhat unusual, and may be a clue to the page's origins. 

The table of contents (which seems to be in an earlier hand than the preceding antiphon) gives Easter II on folio 99; this antiphon is likely an addition to the very end of the antiphoner.

title: California, Private collections, D-0xpcp
summary: Fragmented leaf from a gradual. Fifteenth century (?).
description:
Single leaf from a gradual. Square notation in black ink on red five-line staves with F- and C-clefs; 7 lines per folio side. The textual script appears to be in late Gothic minim style with suggestions of rounded, humanistic pen-strokes. This leaf dates, perhaps, from the late-fifteenth or early-sixteenth century (?). 48.7 x 33.3 cm, with a principal writing space of 37.2 x 23.4 cm. Acquired at an estate sale in California, USA. Currently in the private collection of S. Helak (2018).

The contents do not indicate the feast, but give an introit followed by several gradual verses and rubrics for readings corresponding to the extended reading/responsory material for Ember Saturday in Lent. 
The marginal VACAT is probably calling the user's attention to the fact that the responsory "Protector noster" is not given in full on this leaf. 

Fragmentarium entry: https://fragmentarium.ms/overview/F-xpcp
indexing_notes: The inventory for US-CApc D-0xpcp (fragment) was first drafted by Debra Lacoste during email consultations with the owner of the leaf. The records and manuscript description were entered by Debra Lacoste.The siglum and description were updated with links to Fragmentarium by Anna de Bakker.
indexing_date: 12 August 2018; updated 2021

title: Connecticut USA, Private collections, D-0yp1h
summary: Six parchment fragments from an antiphoner leaf used in the spine of an 18th-century book binding, probably from the early-thirteenth century, with square notation on grey/black four-line staves. Cistercian.
description:
Six binding fragments used for a series of volumes of the "Histoire Ecclesiastique pour servir de continuation à celle de Monsieur l'Abbé Fleury" (Paris, Pierre-Jean Mariette, 1720-30). This group of fragments was part of the spine for vols. 6, 11, and 19. They measure approximately 203 x 152 mm; the present shape is not rectangular, but rather composed of several "comb" shaped pieces which formerly overlapped in the book's spine. The current shape preserves much of the original page height and width, however; it likely measured some 400x300mm in its original state. A roundel reads "xxi" in the lower margin (perhaps a page number or quire number.)

Text hand is praegothica (likely s.13, first half), with curved feet and occasional S and T ligatures (even when the letters are physically separated, the curve is present.) Musical notation is square on a grey/black, four-line staff. Staff height between 12.5 and 14.5 mm. Most notes have a rightward lean, with a stem poking up on the upper right of the note. Connected neumes often have a somewhat curved oblique stroke, with varying thickness. B-flat is present, with a fork in the stem. Both f and c clefs are used, depending on the mode of the chant. The scandicus is sometimes stacked four high. The climacus sometimes has a stem on the left.

The notation suggests a Cistercian provenance, which is corroborated by the contents--a monastic office for St. Benedict using a typically Cistercian ordering and textual variants. However, nothing is known about the provenance prior to its use as a binding fragment.

The fragments from the Ridgefield Project are:
Group A (Gradual): https://cantusdatabase.org/source/1000008
Group B (Antiphoner): https://cantusdatabase.org/source/1000006
Group C (Antiphoner): https://cantusdatabase.org/source/1000007
Group D (Antiphoner): https://cantusdatabase.org/source/1000009
Group E (Antiphoner): https://cantusdatabase.org/source/1000010
Group F (Antiphoner): https://cantusdatabase.org/source/714555
Group G (Antiphoner): https://cantusdatabase.org/source/1000027 Group H (Antiphoner): https://cantusdatabase.org/source/1000028
Group I (Antiphoner): https://cantusdatabase.org/source/1000029
Group J (Antiphoner): (No chant contents) Group K (Antiphoner): https://cantusdatabase.org/source/1000030
Groups L-O, from the Gradual, are yet to be published on Fragmentarium.
In addition, several other fragments possibly pertaining to the same institution(s) were part of the same bindings. https://fragmentarium.ms/view/page/F-036q appears to be a 17th century table of contents or reading, while the many fragments of https://fragmentarium.ms/view/page/F-rv55 have not yet been identified.
selected_bibliography: Fragmentarium: Cistercian antiphoner (Fragment), Ridgefield, CT, Private collection (https://fragmentarium.ms/overview/F-yp1h)
indexing_notes: The fragments in Connecticut USA, Private collections, D-0yp1h were inventoried by Anna de Bakker (Dalhousie University) and proofread by Debra Lacoste (Dalhousie University). This item was contributed by the Ridgefield Fragments Project, a private collection of over 100 pieces of musical and textual manuscript recovered during restoration from the spines of 25 18th-century French books. The owner, who may be contacted via email at  RidgefieldFragments@gmail.com, expresses his thanks for the support of the DACT team and wider academic community.
indexing_date: Indexed in summer 2023; published online on 28 Oct 2023.

title: Phoenix, Private collections, D-0zgch
description:
A single page from an antiphoner, purchased at an antique store in Tucson ca. 1970. 
Five-line staff in red; narrow square notation and plica-like custodes. Small lines as marks of division for each word. Tall and narrow initials in red and blue; text is narrow southern Textualis text, with prescissa minims.Taken together the visual aspects suggest a Spanish origin.  Tall initials, both black with saw teeth and red-and blue filigreed, both popular in the fourteenth century. 

Trimmed along one edge, so that it is no longer rectangular. Measures approximately 437 x 277 mm. 
Writing area is about 330 x 218 mm on the recto and 334 x 224 on the verso. 

Contents are for IV Lent, though in a somewhat unusual order. A verse Galatians 4:23-24 is visible on the recto; this is the end of the Vespers reading for this Sunday. The responsory which follows is more typically a Matins responsory, and may be a clue to the provenance of the fragment. It is followed by a Magnificat antiphon, the typical Vespers collect of IV Lent, and the beginning of the Lauds antiphon. The versicle for Lauds also does not seem to be typical of Lent IV. 

Repetenda of the responsory set off with "p"( which may be another Spanish feature?) Red lines used in the text for melismas, frequently splitting final syllables (a-qui---s; po--pulu---m; e----t.) 

https://fragmentarium.ms/overview/F-zgch

Both three and four-line staves in red; square notation. Somewhat distinctive small b-natural and two-part b-flat signs. Initials seem to have been on blocks slightly larger than the text space provided, causing gaps in some staff lines.

title: Halifax (Nova Scotia), Private Collections, F-nmt3
description:
Two pages from a print gradual, re-purposed as the covers of a notebook (probably after the 1966 flooding of Florence.)
As trimmed, 360 x 215 mm, including a 15mm folded-over edge on 3 sides. Written area 330x 200.

Red staves with black square notation. Diamond-shaped neumes for some unaccented syllables, and a "flipped" virga connecting some neumes. 
Printed text uses ct ligatures and long s; likely 18th century, though recorded by the seller as 17th.

title: California, Private collections, F-rqu3
summary: Single leaf from a gradual. 50 x 35mm. Writing area 40x26 mm.
description:
Single leaf from a gradual (likely Italian, 15th century?). 50 x 35mm. Writing area 40x26 mm. Part of an Alleluia and offertory for Common of Martyrs--but which could have been used for some specific martyr in this case. The presence of the g02346.1 variant does not seem to specify a particular use.
6 red, four-line staves per page. A b-flat (also red) is present, and lines of division of various lengths. Angular, upward-pointing custos. Several basic neume shapes are present in addition to the square punctum: the upper note of the pes is at an angle, while the upper notes of the torculus and clivis have a curve (as do a few other notes).
Text is in Southern Textualis with many fine hairlines. The initial I of the offertory is blue with red penwork and three lines tall; the G of the alleluia verse is similar in height, but entirely red and white with no blue.
Foliated LXXXI, LXXXII on either side.
Obtained as a gift in Basel, Switzerland in 1953.
